{"id":"1909.05792","submitter":"Andrey Brantov","authors":"V. Yu. Bychenkov, M. G. Lobok, V. F. Kovalev, and A. V. Brantov","title":"Generation of high-charge electron beam in a subcritical-density plasma\n  through laser pulse self-trapping","comments":"13 pages, 7 figures","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/1361-6587/ab5142","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.plasm-ph","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  To maximize the charge of a high-energy electron beam accelerated by an\nultra-intense laser pulse propagating in a subcritical plasma, the pulse length\nshould be longer than both the plasma wavelength and the laser pulse width,\nwhich is quite different from the standard bubble regime. In addition, the\nlaser--plasma parameters should be chosen to produce the self-trapping regime\nof relativistic channeling, where the diffraction divergence is balanced by the\nrelativistic nonlinearity such that the laser beam radius is unchanged during\npulse propagation in a plasma over many Rayleigh lengths. The condition for\nsuch a self-trapping regime is the same as what was empirically found in\nseveral previous simulation studies in the form of the pulse width matching\ncondition. Here, we prove these findings for a subcritical plasma, where the\ntotal charge of high-energy electrons reaches the multi-nC level, by\noptimization in a 3D PIC simulation study and compare the results with an\nanalytic theory of relativistic self-focusing. A very efficient explicitly\ndemonstrated generation of high-charge electron beams opens a way to a\nhigh-yield production of gammas, positrons, and photonuclear particles.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Thu, 12 Sep 2019 16:47:32 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-01-08"}
