{"id":"1909.06135","submitter":"Miguel Duarte","authors":"Miguel Duarte, David Hilditch","title":"Conformally flat slices of asymptotically flat spacetimes","comments":"11 pages, 1 figure","journal-ref":null,"doi":"10.1088/1361-6382/ab852b","report-no":null,"categories":"gr-qc","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  For mathematical convenience initial data sets in numerical relativity are\noften taken to be conformally flat. Employing the dual-foliation formalism, we\ninvestigate the physical consequences of this assumption. Working within a\nlarge class of asymptotically flat spacetimes we show that the ADM linear\nmomentum is governed by the leading Lorentz part of a boost even in the\npresence of supertranslation-like terms. Following up, we find that in\nspacetimes that are asymptotically flat, and admit spatial slices with\nvanishing linear momentum that are sufficiently close to conformal flatness,\nany boosted slice can not be conformally flat. Consequently there are no\nconformally flat boosted slices of the Schwarzschild spacetime. This confirms\nthe previously anticipated explanation for the presence of junk-radiation in\nBrandt-Bruegmann puncture data.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Fri, 13 Sep 2019 10:54:17 GMT"}],"update_date":"2020-08-26"}
